            <p facs="#facs_42_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>pour entendre
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/> la¬
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>way, may be one of theZecessities of sehavior. This is certainly not Protestantism, and this
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>certainly does not produce the power of saying No.
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>Now what I want to say no, as the only way I can find, has, let's say, three steps.
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>The first is: All education is education INTO SOMETHING and must have the.introdu ktotory
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>character into a given culture, nation and church, or other groups of cultural cohesion and
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_42_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>symbolism. Second: It must have at the same time the humanistic balance AGAINST the
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>introduction—the structure of man who is able to be creative by himself and therefore has
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>the power of saying No. And with the humanistic, then, can go the introduction into the skills.
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>introductory and the humanistic—the introductory based
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>They balance each other, the
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>on the idea that everything is given, and the humanistic on the basis that the fundamental principles
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>are in man himself by nature.
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>But this balance is an oneasy one. Continually the one is swallowed by the other.
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>And here I can speak about the experiences of the German humanistic Gymnasium, which is
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_10" n="N010"/>high school with an additional two years of College and ends ordinary with 18 or 19 years of
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_2_tl_11" n="N011"/>age. This form of education was very interesting: everything was subjected to the humanities.
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_42_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>But there was ALSO, in the school itself, a kind of religious instruction, at least. And there
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>was in home and church the reality of religion, at least for many people—certainly not for all
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>because thesecularization of Europe was much more advanced than it is in this country. This
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>produced a tremendous conflict in those who werearensitive to BOTH forms of contents, as you
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>can imagine. I myself am an example for it—the conflict between humanism, with its intensive
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>sʼil est vrai que nʼest pas
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>Monsieur, il est vrai avec
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>dʼune manière beaucoup
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_10" n="N010"/>dʼavoir lʼautre ses
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_11" n="N011"/>Mais elle est vrai avec les
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_12" n="N012"/>yours,
               <lb facs="#facs_42_tr_1_tl_13" n="N013"/>dʼune manière
